","1579–1643":"1579–1643","1620–1664":"1620–1664","1550–Male":"1550–Overleden","1555–Female":"1555–Overleden","16 July 1599":"16 juli 1599","1550":"1550","1572":"1572","1579":"1579","1600":"1600","1555":"1555","1643":"1643","1620":"1620","1587":"1587","1664":"1664","1576":"1576","1575":"1575","1585":"1585","about 1620":"circa 1620","about 1572":"circa 1572","Patrixbourne, Bridge, Kent, England":"Patrixbourne, Kent, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Faversham, Kent, England":"Faversham, Kent, England","Canterbury St Margaret, Canterbury, Kent, England":"Canterbury St Margaret, Canterbury, Kent, England","Canterbury, Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Canterbury, Kent, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"about 1572–about 1620":"about 1572–about 1620","1572–1620":"1572–1620","1576–Female":"1576–Deceased","1579–1643":"1579–1643","1620–1664":"1620–1664","1550–Male":"1550–Deceased","1555–Female":"1555–Deceased","16 July 1599":"16 July 1599","1550":"1550","1572":"1572","1579":"1579","1600":"1600","1555":"1555","1643":"1643","1620":"1620","1587":"1587","1664":"1664","1576":"1576","1575":"1575","1585":"1585","about 1620":"about 1620","about 1572":"about 1572","Patrixbourne, Bridge, Kent, England":"Patrixbourne, Kent, England, United Kingdom","Faversham, Kent, England":"Faversham, Kent, England","Canterbury St Margaret, Canterbury, Kent, England":"Canterbury St Margaret, Canterbury, Kent, England","Canterbury, Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Canterbury, Kent, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Beach","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: topographic name from Middle English <i>beche</i> ‘beech-tree’ (Old English <i>bēce</i>) or Middle English <i>beche</i> ‘stream’ (Old English <i>bæce</i>). Middle English <i>beche</i> may be from Old English <i>bēce</i> ‘beech’ or <i>bæce</i> ‘stream’, and without further evidence it is impossible to distinguish these in Middle English.","Americanized form of Alsatian and German <b>Bitsch</b>: habitational name from Bitche (German <i>Bitsch</i>) in Alsace and Lorraine, at the foot of the northern slope of the Vosges.","Americanized form of German (mainly Hesse) <b>Bitsch</b>: unexplained."],"variants":[{"name":"Beech","meanings":["English: variant of   Beach  .","Americanized form of German or Alsatian <b>Bitsch</b> (see   Beach  ) or of some other similar (like-sounding) surname."]},{"name":"Beecher","meanings":["English (Kent): from Middle English <i>becher</i>, denoting one who lived by a beech-tree, from an agent derivative of Middle English <i>beche</i> ‘beech-tree’ (see   Beach  ), the <i>-er</i> suffix having a locative sense. This English name is also common in Ireland, particularly in Cork.","Americanized form of German <b>Bücher</b> (cognate with 1 above) (see   Bucher  )."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705207,"age":13,"year":"1585","julianDay":2299970,"title":"The First English Colony is Established in America","description":"England established its first colony in North America in 1585 as a way to generate additional wealth. The colony was named Virginia, after the virgin Queen Elizabeth I.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705208,"age":15,"year":"1587","julianDay":2300700,"title":"Elizabeth I Signs Death Warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots","description":"Elizabeth I signed the death warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots, on February 1, 1587, as she was found guilty of plotting to assasinate Elizabeth. Mary, Queen of Scots, was beheaded at Fotheringhay Castle in England on February 8, 1587.","url":"https://www.elizabethi.org/mary_queen_of_scots/","urlTitle":"Elizabeth I.org - Mary Queen of Scots","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705210,"age":28,"year":"1600","julianDay":2305448,"title":"The Honourable East India Company","description":"The Honourable East India Company, a British joint-stock company, was established in 1600 for trade in the Indian Ocean region. At its height, the British East India Company had a private army which was twice the size of the British Army, ruled large sections of India, and revenues in the millions.","url":"https://www.historic-uk.com/HistoryUK/HistoryofEngland/The-East-India-Company/","urlTitle":"Historic UK - The East India Company","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705212,"age":48,"year":"1620","julianDay":2312753,"title":"The Pilgrims Board the Mayflower","description":"\"The Pilgrims boarded the Mayflower in search of religious freedom in the New World in September 1620. The Mayflower set sail from Plymouth, England, with 102 passengers, 40 of whom called themselves \"\"Saints.\"\" After two stormy months at sea, the ship reached the New World. Nearly half of the group died during their first winter due to malnutrition and the harsh New England winter.\"","url":"https://www.themayflowersociety.org/the-pilgrims/pilgrim-history","urlTitle":"The Mayflower Society - Pilgrim History","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert Beach was born about 1572, in Faversham, Kent, England, his father, Thomas Beach, was 23 and his mother, Alice Wilcox, was 18. He married Agnes Bowker on 16 July 1599, in Canterbury St Margaret, Canterbury, Kent, England. He died about 1620, in Canterbury, Kent, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 50."},"et":{"about 1572–about 1620":"umbes 1572–umbes 1620","1572–1620":"1572–1620","1576–Female":"1576–Surnud","1579–1643":"1579–1643","1620–1664":"1620–1664","1550–Male":"1550–Surnud","1555–Female":"1555–Surnud","16 July 1599":"16. juuli 1599","1550":"1550","1572":"1572","1579":"1579","1600":"1600","1555":"1555","1643":"1643","1620":"1620","1587":"1587","1664":"1664","1576":"1576","1575":"1575","1585":"1585","about 1620":"umbes 1620","about 1572":"umbes 1572","Patrixbourne, Bridge, Kent, England":"Patrixbourne, Kent, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Faversham, Kent, England":"Faversham, Kent, England","Canterbury St Margaret, Canterbury, Kent, England":"Canterbury St Margaret, Canterbury, Kent, England","Canterbury, Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Canterbury, Kent, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1572–about 1620":"noin 1572–noin 1620","1572–1620":"1572–1620","1576–Female":"1576–Kuollut","1579–1643":"1579–1643","1620–1664":"1620–1664","1550–Male":"1550–Kuollut","1555–Female":"1555–Kuollut","16 July 1599":"16. heinäkuuta 1599","1550":"1550","1572":"1572","1579":"1579","1600":"1600","1555":"1555","1643":"1643","1620":"1620","1587":"1587","1664":"1664","1576":"1576","1575":"1575","1585":"1585","about 1620":"noin 1620","about 1572":"noin 1572","Patrixbourne, Bridge, Kent, England":"Patrixbourne, Kent, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Faversham, Kent, England":"Faversham, Kent, England","Canterbury St Margaret, Canterbury, Kent, England":"Canterbury St Margaret, Canterbury, Kent, England","Canterbury, Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Canterbury, Kent, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"about 1572–about 1620":"environ 1572–environ 1620","1572–1620":"1572–1620","1576–Female":"1576–Décédée","